	abstract = {Explores the importance of the snakebite survivor as a core symbol in the conceptual order of medicine practice among Ngawbe, inhabitants of an indigenous reserve in Panama. Based on more than 2 yrs of field research among the Ngawbe, it appears that at a conceptual level, snakes and snake-related phenomena are associated with sexual rather than gustatory appetites. Whereas snake-related dreams (SRDs) are reported and associated with real-life events of snake sightings and killings, the rarer occurrence of actual snakebite is not generally linked in public discourse with an SRD. The informational limits of SRDs and events are defined by one's network of cognatic and affinal kinsmen. A dream about a snakebite survivor camouflages the true identity of the person linked to one's frustration over a thwarted expectation. SRDs are reported only when their manifest content is auspicious and appears relevant to the day's activities. (PsycLIT Database Copyright 1992 American Psychological Assn, all rights reserved)},
