	abstract = {Confronting the risk of emerging infectious diseases of wildlife is an\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nimportant objective for biosecurity and conservation. Batrachochytrium\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ndendrobatidis (Bd), cause of the emerging disease chytridiomycosis, has\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nbeen associated with amphibian declines and extinctions globally.\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nCharacterizing Bd's host range is important for understanding community\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ndisease dynamics, predicting further declines, minimizing the cost of\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nsurveillance and developing pre-emptive management actions. In this\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nstudy, we integrated ametric of potential host exposure to the pathogen\${\textbackslash}backslash\$n(derived from spatial models of environmental suitability for Bd) with\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nhost species' life-history and ecological traits to identify risk\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nfactors associated with Bd infection in our model system (Australia). We\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nfound that the most informative predictor of a species' infection status\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nwas their general occupancy in areas predicted to be environmentally\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nsuitable for Bd. Body size, range size, habitat association, and Family\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nwere also important but were less useful for prediction. This\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ninformation allowed us to make predictions regarding infection risk in\${\textbackslash}backslash\$npoorly or unstudied species and shortlist new potential hosts for\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ntargeted future surveillance. Our study highlights the utility of\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nspecies distribution modeling for wildlife diseases and examines the\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nrole of sampling bias and host life-history traits in risk analyses for\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nchytridiomycosi